14 WHEREAS, there is a need for a comprehensive review of systems of care for people with
15 disabilities.
16 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
17 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
18 on an At-Risk Populations Abuse Registry.
19 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of eight members to be
20 appointed as follows:
21 (A) Three members of the House of Representatives to be appointed by the Speaker
22 of the House of Representatives, one of whom the Speaker shall designate as
23 chairperson of the committee; and
24 (B) Five nonlegislative members to be appointed by the Speaker of the House of
25 Representatives as follows:
26 (i) The commissioner of public health or his or her designee;
27 (ii) A citizen representative from a state-wide protection and advocacy organization
28 for individuals with disabilities;
29 (iii) A citizen representative from a state-wide elder rights advocacy organization;
30 (iv) A representative from the Prosecuting Attorneys' Council of the State of Georgia;
31 and
32 (v) A citizen representative who is either a person with intellectual and
33 developmental disabilities or a person in a care facility.
34 (3) Powers and duties. The committee shall undertake a study of the conditions, needs,
35 issues, and problems mentioned above or related thereto and recommend any action or
36 legislation which the committee deems necessary or appropriate. As part of the
37 committee's work, the committee shall:
38 (A) Conduct a comprehensive review of Tennessee's substantiated abuse registry and
39 similar models in other states;
